<exercise checkit-seed="0004" checkit-slug="PS4" checkit-title="Taylor series">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>f(x)</m> be a function such that:
            
            <me>
                \begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
                f(0) &amp; f'(0) &amp; f''(0) &amp; f'''(0) &amp; f^{(4)}(0) &amp; f^{(5)}(0) &amp; f^{(6)}(0) \\
                \hline
                -5 &amp; 15 &amp; -45 &amp; 135 &amp; -405 &amp; 1215 &amp; -3645 
                \end{array}
            </me>
            
            <ol>
                <li>Find a Taylor polynomial for <m>f(x)</m> centered at <m>x=0</m> of degree <m>2</m>.</li>
                <li>Using the table above, find a general closed form for <m>f^{(n)}(0)</m>.</li>
                <li>Use (b) to find a Taylor series for <m>f(x)</m> centered at <m>x=0</m>.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </statement>
    <answer>
            <ol>
                <li><m>f_{ 2 }(x)=-\frac{45}{2} \, x^{2} + 15 \, x - 5</m>.</li>
                <li><m>f^{(n)}(0)=-5 \cdot 3^{n} \left(-1\right)^{n}</m>.</li>
                <li><m>\displaystyle f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{ -5 \cdot 3^{n} \left(-1\right)^{n} }{n!} (x-0)^n</m>.</li>
            </ol>
    </answer>
</exercise>
